	   <tr><td colspan=2>Pusbag now had been under the spell of the lizard, Gezz, for many days-- weeks perhaps.&nbsp;&nbsp;Time seemed to drag on as he followed his master through Kunark killing indiscriminately at the whim of his &quot;owner&quot;.<br><br>He had one thing to be grateful for and that was that due to the enormous amount of death he dispensed upon any living thing they came across, the iksar had allowed him to feed freely upon the corpses.  His stomach no longer growled constantly and he in return ended the lives of a proportionate number of victims for his master.<br><br>Pusbag noted that there was a small part of him which was not given over to the iksar who commanded his actions, a part which objectively analyzed his behavior and movements.  It was this tiny piece of free will that Pusbag hoarded like it was a gem of enormous price.  He refused to relinquish this bit of his spirit and hid it from the scaly creature manipulating him.<br><br>*************************************************************<br><br>Gezz the Iksar enjoyed playing with the Troll, making him do as he chose, especially knowing that it would cause Pusbag's teeth to grind if he were able to make such a movement on his own-- which, pleasingly, he wasn't!  It was a wonder to see this extraordinarily powerful Troll kill various creatures with a style of fighting unlike anything he had ever seen or even heard of.  The giant Troll combined a weapon style with a rare unarmed combat kata, which rendered him virtually undefeatable in a fight.  He marveled at the fortune of whoever had luck to bring Pusbag to where he was today-- in his geas.  Whoever it was must have barely escaped with his life, since to face this deadly Troll was like entering the Arena unarmed versus a squadron of enraged spectres intent on evicerating you. <br><br>He noticed the Troll was hungry by the coveteous eyes he cast on his victims, so he granted permission to the Troll to take his fill.  Watching him eat, the iksar's jaw dropped at the prodigious appetite of the colossal Troll.  He ate continually and with abandon, as if he expected to never take a bite of food ever again.  Incredible!<br><br>Thinking about the present situation, Gezz was grateful that the Troll was unable to cast his magical spells since that would mean he had regained his will.  Yikes!  The thought of facing Pusbag intent on revenge using <i>all of his skills-- combat and magical</i>, was one which caused an involuntary shiver to pass down his spine.  And for a creature as an Iksar, fear was an emotion that they as a race were most unfamiliar with.  What an uncomfortable feeling!  He was glad he was a member of the superior race and one who had Usula to lead them into glory.  It was inevitable for the iksar to rule.  It was destiny!<br><br>On this thought, he shrugged off the taint of fear and commanded his Troll to follow.  They had a destination to get to and all this introspection served no purpose but to delay his plans.  He would soon see if Pusbag's weapons prowess were the match for a dragon.<br><br>Destiny.  <i>This</i> was a thought on which the iksar should spend energy.  Soon, very soon they would do what this <i>mere</i> Troll could not do-- rule the world.<br><br>--Pusbag Infection <br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Feb 19 15:45:40 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Emperor and Shamanic High Priest of the Trolls<br>"Worship Innoruuk, you worthless cattle!"<br></td></tr>
