	   <tr><td colspan=2>Culris proceeded to his private quarters, beneath the grotto of the keeper's hidden from any prying eyes within New Sebilis. It was there he would meet the three, and begin their dark enchantments.<br>Many saw Culris round Cabilis, and only thought he was a slave to Usula, at beck and call, or the most, he was mearly a jumped up spy who dabbled in the dark arts. However, Culris possesed much knowledge, and in his travels, he had encountered many a fasinating tome, containing scriptures about the nature of each race, including the trolls and the elves. From this he gained the knowledge that there is only one type of elf.<br>This was shocking to him, but as he read more, he began to understand, for elves are muich like gems, turn them, move them, and you will see different shapes and colours, but it will still be the same thing. Such were elves, the High Elves were the side that was noble, and wise, the Wood Elves were natureous and loving for all that lived, and the Dark Elves were cunning, plotting and intelligent. However, since the begining, Innoruk seperated out these parts, and watered them down with the blood of the humans, and so this oneness was lost, and the elves began feuding with each other, no longer a one people, but many races, each different. But there in lied the answer to the question, how do you destroy and elf? Since elves are immortal, they cannot die truely, they can be killed, and certainly, their bodies can be burned, but they will simply be born again, in a new, strong body, but the same spirit will endure. No, to kill an elf, you must destroy the spirit, and in one of the darkest tomes, in the blackest dungeons, in the most evil of lands, he had found how to do this. Indeed, the knowledge had very nearly cost him his life, since tomes such as these do not give secrets easily.<br>Entering the room of incantation within his quarters, he saw already the Three has assembled, each acknowledging him with a slight nod. They had been busy, for the circle of Rites had been drawn, the the three corners defined. There only remained the components, and the spell itself.<br>&quot;You have what i sent each to get yes?&quot; He queried<br>&quot;Aye&quot; each replied and presented him, in turn, with a corked up vial, and each he placed in a rack. One was filled with a emerald leaf green, a pure colour of nature, the blood of a Fier'Dal druid, a priest among the Fier'Dal. The second was filled with pure black, that seemed to glow, if such a thing was possible. This black was not the matt black of deadness, but was a black that was alive in its feeling, an example of pure darkness, taken from a Tier'Dal priest or Innoruk, a necromancer. The third vial contained a reddish pink substance, not bright pink, but the pink of new born flesh of the humans. This was the blood of the Homodia'Dal, half elves, and from a paladin, holy knight who linked Tunare and the Marr twins in an alliance. When all three were placed in the rack, Culris removed the fourth vial, that was secreated about his person. This was the blue blood he took from the evoker of the Koada'Dal. He placed this in the last slot of the rack, and carried it to the center with him.<br>&quot;Take your daggers, and form the circle&quot;<br>Each of the three took station on one of the points, on the outer edge of the circle, where the three corners had been drawn. Once they had, they began to chant, cerimonial daggers in hand, and sawying in motion. Culris donned his black robe, and took position in the centre of the cirlce. Although there were no instruments, the air seemed to fill with beats rom drums, deep and filled with bass.<br>&quot;I call upon the dark powers!&quot; the chanting contined the word powers<br>&quot;I call upon the unholy trinity&quot;<br>&quot;trinity, trinty, trinity...&quot;<br>&quot;Innoruk, Brextoxxilos, Cazic-Thule!&quot;<br>&quot;Thule Thule, Thuel...&quot;<br>&quot;Take this offerings, and make them into what they should be!&quot;<br>&quot;be, be, be, be...&quot;<br>&quot;Hear us, head our call&quot;<br>&quot;call, call, call..&quot;<br>&quot;Give us, as trust us, as we trust YOU!&quot;<br>And with the call, each necromancer thrust their dagger into their heart, and fell, as totally darkness filled the whole room.<br>When they awoke, many hours later, the four necromancers found their daggers stabbed far into the ground, one at the end of each point, and Culris' in the exact centre of the room. And, balancing on the hilt of the centre dagger was...<br>Light, pure white light, captured within a vial of liquid.<br>&quot;What is it..?&quot; one of the Three whispered<br>Laughing out, Culris answered<br>&quot;It's what we asked for! There is only one way to kill and elf, and that is with the blood of the true elf! This is what we have, Dal Blood, or as it will be Dal Bane! They took our offerings and combined them! We have the key to the downfall of the elven races!&quot;<br>With that, he grabbed the vial, and wrenched his dagger from the ground. Then he put a bung in the vial's end, and hid it among his robe and left his chambers, still leaving the Three there, to contemplate what had happened, and to clean up the chalk and candles..<br>&nbsp;<br>Culris Wurmbane<br>Lord of the Brood<br>Mithaniel Marr</td></tr>
