	   <tr><td colspan=2>The return to Cabilis, while without great fanfare, was truly a triumph for Usula.&nbsp;&nbsp;Though she would never say it, she was most pleased with the competent and capable warrior Eiczk proved himself to be.  Truly, she thought, her trust in the legionnaire was not misplaced.  She hoped he would find some small use for the token reward she had given him, but his occasional scowls only produced a fit of chuckling in her.<br><br>In Cabilis, after she had dismissed Eiczk to whatever entertainment he wished to partake of, Usula met with Culris.<br><br><span style='color: green;'>&quot;The Tier Dal are as arrogant as I had expected.  It was sheer ease that allowed my party to sneak into Neriak and steal some of their precious journals on Necromancy.  I think we shall benefit greatly in the knowledge of their arts.'</span style='color: green;'>  Usula stated.<br><br>Culris examined the texts and had to grudgingly admit that the knowledge contained therein was new, even for practiced members of the Brood of Kotiz.  They would add much power to the Iksar, of that he was sure.<br><br>Usula went on to describe the layout of the city in detail, including the general layout of the land, the guard posts, and the most prominent members and guild leaders.  All of this was valuable information if Culris was to pull off the plan he had so long worked to complete.  When her report was complete, Usula retired to her personal chambers in order to study some of the works she had taken.  Her personal interest was taken by the book <i>Mind Wrack and the Essence of Magic</i> by one Lyxol X&amp;#8217;Tempo.  Apparently, the Tier Dal necromancer had discovered a way to steal the manna essence of an individual creature and spread it out to up to six companions.  Usula wondered how this spell could be used in conjunction with a contingent of Shadow Knights and Shaman (vile creatures they may be, but still Iksar) against a highly magical foe.  Usula wondered if the spell would work, and if they would work against Dragons.  She studied the text the entire night and well into the next day before finally exiting her chambers.<br><br>Summoning a skeletal monk pet named Xabober, she sent him off to fetch Eiczk to her chambers.  At that time, Eiczk was in the Field of Bone, overseeing several young recruits.  He was not surprised, however, at the summons of the necromancer.  With determination mixed with a small amount of dread, he entered into her chambers.<br><br>She was seated on the floor, as was her custom, in the reception room.  Looming above her was the tapestry showing the defeat of the Iksar so long ago.  Eiczk had never become used to the unsettling tapestry.  With a flick of her wrist and a glance from her poison green eyes, Usula gestured for Eiczk to sit across from her.  Seeing no way to politely refuse, he did as he was bidden.  Usula was drinking something from a flask, and offered him a cup.<br><br><span style='color: green;'>&quot;I believe you are now worthy, Eiczk.  You are both brave and knowledgeable, a very commendable combination.  Ask me what you will, Eiczk, and I shall answer.&quot;</span style='color: green;'><br><br>&nbsp;<br>Usula Wurmbane<br>Iksar Necromancer<br>Empress of Fear</td></tr>
