	   <tr><td colspan=2>Eizck stood in the midst of Warsliks Woods, working sword-forms. They helped him relax, and focus himself. He may not be a monk, but Glox had taught him a thing or two to control his anger when he was younger. The blade circled him as if moving of a will of its own. Arcing through tight circles, then shifting as if to parry an invisible blow. It helped him forget pain. His thoughts fled back to what happened in Grobb.<br><br><i>The troll moved very quickly for one of its girth. His axe came sweeping at Eiczk's head, but the iksar warrior dodged, spun around and decapitated the troll. &quot;So much for another of these foolish guards.&quot; he said. Another troll advanced, sword in hand. at the same time he saw Pusbag leap at Culris. Eiczk moved to stop him, but pain struck him like a boulder. He could not move. The troll swordsman had pinned him against a rock like a goblin on a spit. Fear fled into him with a vengance. Culris' death would mean great pain for the one who had brought him here, instead of mounting his head on the walls of Cabilis. He snarled at the foul green blob grinning at him, his eyes sinking from green to a fiery red. He spun his offhand sword, striking upwards. The beast's arm fell to the ground. With the trollish sword sticking out of his shoulder, Eiczk leaped towards where he saw pusbag. Fear filled him, he would not fail Usula. Using momentum to swing his damaged arm, he brought the butt handle of his main blade down on Pusbag's skull. It made a very satisfying &quot;Crunch&quot;. Pusbag would be left to Usula to handle, as it would take more than a weak knock on the head to kill a troll. Smiling he turned to see the crushed body of Culris, all joy fled. He pulled the sword free of his own body, and turned to face the armless swordsman who had delayed his attack on Pusbag. &quot;You will pay for this, food!&quot; said the warrior. Eiczk plunged the troll's blade through his skull, and the corpse dropped like a sack of bad veinworms. He had failed to protect the Clutchmate of a council member. He looked at Usula seeing sadness in her eyes, and shared in her pain. He had liked Culris, for what little time he knew him.</I><br><br>Fear controls us, gives us strength. Draw on it and you will never fail. Eiczk heard the words of his father calling from the distant past. He ran his fingers across an old scar on his ribs. That had been given to him by trolls long ago when he first set foot on Antonica. He had gone to Grobb to seek food and supplies. They greeted him as if he were one of the Softskins. He remembered the darkness of Grobb all too well. Escape had been only thanks to a young troll who had never seen an iksar before. The troll had healed him a little, but could not heal many of the wounds inflicted. Especially the wound upon his ribs. One of the Troll shaman had sliced his ribs open, tormenting nerves. Neither shaman nor necromancer had been able to heal that scar. He hated the Green foul beasts. They stunk, and tasted nasty. However their meat made excellent field rations. The Legionnaire focused back on the present realzing that someone had been saying his name. To him it had been a distant wind blowing through the trees. &quot;Umm.. Legionnaire? are you alright?&quot; said one of the nearby troopers. &quot;I'm fine. I was just deep in thought. what is it Trooper?&quot; The trooper advanced slowly and spoke again &quot;Well sir, I come from the western post. we... um... well you see... One of the giant prisoners has run amok, and killed several of the guards.&quot; Eiczk sighed. &quot;And you were where Trooper? I instructed you to stand on hand to stay any &quot;rebelious thoughts&quot; the few remaining prisoners would have. They are useful in our naval construction.&quot; &quot;Well sir,&quot; continued the trooper. &quot;I was following what I thought was a goblin that escaped. You know, the tunnels to the lake and all still being checked.&quot; Eiczk raised an eyeridge at the thought. &quot;Yes Trooper I know. How unfortunate.&quot; <br><br>Eiczk stepped towards the trooper, and brought his sword up in a sweeping motion, ending with the blade pointing to the sky.&nbsp;&nbsp;The trooper fell to the ground, split from groin to skull. &quot;Mount this rubbish on the walls of the western outpost. You there, soldier!&quot; He pointed to one of the soldiers, whom he had fought with in grobb. &quot;You are to proceed with 15 more soldiers to reinforce that post. Make sure that the slaves work as they need to. I will handle that rouge Giant. Do not disobey me. Others will watch for goblins, though I doubt we will see many free anytime soon. move it, Trooper!&quot; The soldier smiled at being raised in rank. Eiczk knew this one would not fail him. &quot;Also, if by some chance you do see it to follow shadows as your predecessor did, know this. I will not kill anymore men. However those whom are too weak to serve will be turned over to the Brood for punishment. I gave the trooper Mercy for his weakness, the Brood will not. NOW GO!&quot; <br><br>He barked the last of this as the trooper and 15 soldiers peeled off towards the western fort. One drug the garbage that was the ex-commander of the outer fort. Eiczk managed a grin, the body would keep fear working the soldiers as much as the threat of being turned over to Necromancers. He really did not want to loose anymore soldiers. Every last member of the Legion, from the warlords down to the Partisans knew what had happened to Pusbag. They did not want to face that punishment. The fallen are the best example, he remembered his father saying. Eiczk turned towards the building where he had set up camp for the time being, only to see Footman Moglok standing there. &quot;Yes footman, what is it?&quot; he snapped. &quot;Well, sir I come with a summons from the lady Usula, she has need of you.&quot; the Legionnaire sighed, Fear gave him strength. Perhaps today was the day he died for his failure.&quot;Very well footman, Oh since you failed Warlord Vyzer in returning the Gubnubb brothers' heads, I have a task for you. Go out to the outer fort, near the entrance to the Overthere. There is a Rouge Giant loose. Bring me his head, or I will assume he has yours. I will make a decent trooper of you yet Moglok.&quot; The footman ran off into the woods as Eiczk ran towards Cabilis. Fear drove him to obey, and gave him strength.<br><br>/OOC ON<br>Sorry I have not posted recently, other familial duties took a higher priority. I must say, interesting twist all :) I look forward to see where this goes.<br>/OOC OFF<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Feb 12 16:04:26 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Eiczk Draygoner<br>34th rank Warrior<br>Legionnaire of Cabilis<br>Xegony<br><i>-Death comes to all, but for the fallen it shall come with a vengance.</i></td></tr>
